        desc: "California's largest river by volume — the Sacramento flows 400 miles from Mount Shasta to the San Francisco Bay Delta. The upper river below Shasta Dam runs cold and clear through pastoral Shasta and Tehama counties, supporting the state's most important salmon runs. A big-water float through the heart of Northern California's agricultural valley.",
        desig: 'National Wild & Scenic River (upper section) · Sacramento River National Wildlife Refuge',
        secs: ['Redding to Red Bluff — 60 mi, cold tailwater, prime salmon water', 'Red Bluff to Colusa — 80 mi, riparian corridor, wildlife refuge', 'Upper Sacramento above Shasta Lake — Class II–III, mountain run'],
        history: [
          { era: 'native', entries: [{ yr: 'Pre-contact', title: "Wintu People — River of the North", text: "The upper Sacramento River was the homeland of the Wintu people, who depended on massive salmon runs that once numbered in the millions. The Wintu maintained a sustainable relationship with the river for thousands of years before gold mining and dam construction devastated both the fishery and their way of life.", src: 'Winnemem Wintu Tribe; California State Parks' }] },
          { era: 'modern', entries: [{ yr: '2024', title: 'Sacramento River Salmon Recovery Initiative', text: "State and federal agencies launched a comprehensive salmon recovery initiative focused on habitat restoration, flow management below Shasta Dam, and floodplain reconnection along the Sacramento River. The effort aims to reverse decades of decline in winter-run Chinook salmon, listed as endangered since 1994.", src: 'NOAA Fisheries; California Department of Fish and Wildlife' }] },
        ],
        docs: [],
        revs: [],
        outs: [],
